---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import FAQ from '../../../components/FAQ.astro';
import { articleSchema, breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../lib/schema';

const title = 'Best Robot Lawn Mowers UK 2026 - Ranked';
const description = 'The best robot mowers for UK gardens in 2026. Wire-free and perimeter wire models compared from specs and verified owner reviews - Husqvarna, Mammotion, Worx.';
const path = '/robot-lawn-mowers/best/';
const datePublished = '2026-05-10';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Robot lawn mowers', url: '/robot-lawn-mowers/' },
  { name: 'Best 2026', url: path },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Are robot lawn mowers worth it in the UK?',
    a: 'If your lawn is over 200 m² and you mow regularly, yes. You\'ll get back 1-2 hours a week, the lawn actually looks better (little-and-often cutting is healthier for grass), and modern models handle UK rain and slopes without issue.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do robot mowers work in the rain?',
    a: 'Most modern robot mowers are rated IPX5 or higher and will mow in light rain. Some models (Husqvarna, EGO) have rain sensors that send them back to the dock in heavy rain to avoid tearing wet turf.',
  },
];

const schema = [
  breadcrumbSchema(crumbs),
  articleSchema({ headline: title, description, url: path, datePublished }),
  faqSchema(faqs),
].filter(Boolean);
---
<BaseLayout {title} {description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">
    <Breadcrumbs items={crumbs} />

    <header class="mb-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-grass-700 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">Robot Guide · Updated May 2026</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-soil-900 leading-tight">Best Robot Lawn Mowers UK 2026</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        Never mow again - or at least, that's the promise. We've compared robot mowers from Husqvarna, Mammotion and Worx against specs and verified owner reviews to find out which ones actually deliver.
      </p>
    </header>

    <img
      src="/images/compact_robotic_lawn_mower.webp"
      alt="Robot lawn mower cutting a UK garden autonomously"
      width="900" height="506"
      class="w-full rounded-xl mb-10 object-cover"
      loading="eager"
    />

    <div class="prose-mowers">
      <h2>Wire-free vs perimeter wire - the big decision</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional robot mowers need a buried perimeter wire to define your lawn edges. It works, but installation takes a day and the wire breaks if you aerate. Wire-free models use cameras or RTK GPS instead - no installation, no buried cable, and you can move them between lawns. In 2026, wire-free is where the market's heading.
      </p>

      <h2>Three robot mowers we recommend</h2>

      <h3>1. Husqvarna Automower 305 (£799)</h3>
      <p>
        The most reliable robot mower on the market. Husqvarna invented the category in 1995 and the 305 is their entry-level model for lawns up to 600 m². Perimeter wire required, but the cutting quality and app control are excellent. <a href="/reviews/husqvarna-automower-305/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Husqvarna 305 review</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Mammotion Luba 2 AWD 1000 (£1,399)</h3>
      <p>
        The best wire-free robot mower available. RTK GPS navigation, all-wheel drive for slopes up to 38°, and handles lawns up to 1,000 m² with multiple zones. Setup takes 20 minutes with a phone app instead of a day burying wire. <a href="/reviews/mammotion-luba-2-awd-1000/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Mammotion Luba review</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Worx Landroid Vision M800 (£999)</h3>
      <p>
        Worx's camera-based wire-free mower for lawns up to 800 m². The AI vision system handles obstacles well and the modular design lets you add GPS, voice control or off-road wheels later. <a href="/reviews/worx-landroid-vision-m800/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Worx Vision review</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What about security?</h2>
      <p>
        Robot mowers get stolen. The good ones have PIN codes, alarm systems, GPS tracking and lift sensors that trigger an alert. Husqvarna and Mammotion both offer GPS tracking as standard. Always register your mower's serial number and check your home insurance covers garden equipment.
      </p>
    </div>

    <FAQ {faqs} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
